In Selenium (Java), the Options classes are used to configure browser-specific settings before launching the browser. They let you control how the browser behaves—things like running in headless mode, setting arguments, handling certificates, or customizing profiles.
🔹 What is Options Class?
In Selenium WebDriver, each browser has its own Options class:
ChromeOptions → for Chrome
FirefoxOptions → for Firefox
EdgeOptions → for Edge
These classes extend a common base and allow you to customize browser capabilities.
🔹 Why use Options class?
You use it when you want to:
Run tests in headless mode (no UI)
Disable notifications or popups
Set browser window size
Accept insecure SSL certificates
Add extensions
Customize browser behavior for automation
🔹 Example: ChromeOptions in Java
Java
import org.openqa.selenium.WebDriver;
import org.openqa.selenium.chrome.ChromeDriver;
import org.openqa.selenium.chrome.ChromeOptions;

public class OptionsExample {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        ChromeOptions options = new ChromeOptions();
        
        // Add arguments
        options.addArguments("--start-maximized");
        options.addArguments("--disable-notifications");
        
        // Headless mode
        options.addArguments("--headless=new");
        
        // Accept insecure certificates
        options.setAcceptInsecureCerts(true);

        WebDriver driver = new ChromeDriver(options);
        driver.get("https://example.com");
    }
}
🔹 Common Methods in Options Class
1. addArguments()
Used to pass browser arguments:
Java
options.addArguments("--incognito");
options.addArguments("--disable-gpu");
2. setExperimentalOption()
Used for advanced settings:
Java
options.setExperimentalOption("excludeSwitches", 
                              Arrays.asList("enable-automation"));
3. setAcceptInsecureCerts(true)
Accepts SSL certificate errors.
4. setCapability()
Used to merge capabilities:
Java
options.setCapability("browserVersion", "latest");
🔹 FirefoxOptions Example
Java
FirefoxOptions options = new FirefoxOptions();
options.addArguments("-private");
WebDriver driver = new FirefoxDriver(options);
🔹 Key Interview Points
Options class is used to customize browser launch settings
It replaces older DesiredCapabilities (now mostly deprecated)
Each browser has its own Options class
It is passed to WebDriver during initialization
🔹 Simple Real-Time Use Case
In real projects, you might:
Disable notifications for login automation
Run tests in headless mode in CI/CD pipelines
Use incognito mode to avoid cache issues
